text: It would be nice if producers in hollywood tried to give a realistic tone and scientific points in mythological based movies.  For example Hercules would be awesome if you had a really strong man and his soldiers and friends trying to help cities and villages from monster attacks. These monsters though would be the last of real prehistoric species or people with mutations (from birth) like a huge man with one eye, giants, people with many hands and stuff/ I am pretty sure this is how mythology in every culture created. People saw monstrosities, abominations and prehistoric species,fossils and skeletons, natural events they could not explain so they had to name them, create spiritual connections, powerful entities so they could live hero prototypes for the next generations and a system of control in early societies.   As a Greek though I like the brute, beard, muscular Herakles this movie portrays. I know it will have a lot of CGI but staying true to the comic and as true as possible to the mythos, is what I wanna watch.  We will see.

text: I think it's a shame that at least some films based on mythological tales (which are experiencing a new golden era as of a couple of years ago) aren't portayed as the often horrid and gruesome original texts that they derive from. I would be jazzed to see a more serious and dark take on Greek mythology with fewer special effects, more intrigue, complex characters, chocking life decisions and also more build-up story-wise. It's not all about effects, most new films based on Greek mythology lack heart, soul and tragedy. The heroes of Greek mythology were often selfish and cruel and the good guy did not always win.

text: I enjoyed this film, it was fun. But man this trailer seriously misrepresents the film though! Yes, the actual film is pretty tongue-in-cheek, and while that plays to DJs strengths as a performer, I still would have hoped for a more compelling story. I loved the supporting cast, and I thought DJ did a great job overall.
